{"opportunities":[{"filePath":"src/PublicApi/CatalogBrandEndpoints/CatalogBrandListEndpoint.cs","title":"Cache static catalog brands in memory","scope":"narrow","rootCause":"## Evidence\n\nAt `CatalogBrandListEndpoint.cs:40`, every request to `/api/catalog-brands` executes a full database query:\n\n```csharp\nvar items = await catalogBrandRepository.ListAsync();\n```\n\nCatalog brands are static reference data (~5 rows) that never change during a load test run. Yet every single k6 iteration triggers a fresh DB round-trip. The application already registers `IMemoryCache` at `Program.cs:53`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.Services.AddMemoryCache();\n```\n\nbut no endpoint uses it.\n\n## Theory\n\nEach of the ~50 concurrent VUs calls `/api/catalog-brands` once per iteration, generating hundreds of identical SELECT queries per second against a table that returns the same 5 rows every time. While each query is fast individually, the cumulative DB connection overhead, EF object materialisation, and AutoMapper projection add up â€” especially under contention. Caching this tiny, immutable dataset in `IMemoryCache` eliminates the DB round-trip, EF tracking, and mapper allocation entirely for the vast majority of requests.\n\n## Proposed Fixes\n\n1. **Inject `IMemoryCache` and cache brand list:** In `CatalogBrandListEndpoint`, inject `IMemoryCache` via the constructor. In `HandleAsync`, use `GetOrCreateAsync` with a short TTL (e.g., 30-60 seconds) to cache the mapped `List<CatalogBrandDto>`. Return the cached list on subsequent calls, skipping the repository and mapper entirely.\n\n## Expected Impact\n\n- p95 latency: ~0.1-0.2ms reduction on affected requests by eliminating DB + EF + AutoMapper overhead\n- RPS: slight improvement from reduced DB connection contention\n- The `/api/catalog-brands` endpoint accounts for ~14.3% of total traffic (1 of 7 requests per iteration). Eliminating the DB round-trip should reduce per-request latency by ~0.15ms, yielding ~1-2% overall p95 improvement.","impactEstimate":{"trafficPct":14.3,"latencyReductionMs":0.15,"overallP95ImprovementPct":1.2,"confidence":"medium","reasoning":"Brands endpoint is 1 of 7 requests per iteration (~14.3% traffic). Eliminating DB round-trip for static data saves ~0.15ms per request. At 1.77ms p95, this yields roughly 1.2% overall improvement."}},{"filePath":"src/PublicApi/CatalogTypeEndpoints/CatalogTypeListEndpoint.cs","title":"Cache static catalog types in memory","scope":"narrow","rootCause":"## Evidence\n\nAt `CatalogTypeListEndpoint.cs:40`, every request to `/api/catalog-types` performs a database query for static reference data:\n\n```csharp\nvar items = await catalogTypeRepository.ListAsync();\n```\n\nCatalog types are a tiny, immutable reference table (~4 rows). Like brands, this endpoint is called once per k6 iteration but never uses the already-registered `IMemoryCache` service (`Program.cs:53`).\n\n## Theory\n\nIdentical to the brands analysis: under 50 concurrent VUs, hundreds of identical SELECT queries per second hit the types table. Each query incurs DB connection acquisition, EF materialisation, and AutoMapper projection for the same 4 rows. Caching removes all three costs. Combined with brand caching, this eliminates 2 of 7 DB queries per iteration (~28.6% of read traffic), reducing overall DB connection pressure and freeing thread pool threads for write operations.\n\n## Proposed Fixes\n\n1. **Inject `IMemoryCache` and cache type list:** In `CatalogTypeListEndpoint`, inject `IMemoryCache` via the constructor. In `HandleAsync`, use `GetOrCreateAsync` with a short TTL (e.g., 30-60 seconds) to cache the mapped `List<CatalogTypeDto>`. Return cached data on subsequent calls.\n\n## Expected Impact\n\n- p95 latency: ~0.1-0.2ms reduction on affected requests\n- RPS: slight improvement from reduced DB connection contention (cumulative with brand caching)\n- The `/api/catalog-types` endpoint accounts for ~14.3% of total traffic. Eliminating the DB round-trip should reduce per-request latency by ~0.15ms, yielding ~1-2% overall p95 improvement.","impactEstimate":{"trafficPct":14.3,"latencyReductionMs":0.15,"overallP95ImprovementPct":1.2,"confidence":"medium","reasoning":"Types endpoint is 1 of 7 requests per iteration (~14.3% traffic). Eliminating DB round-trip for static data saves ~0.15ms per request. At 1.77ms p95, this yields roughly 1.2% overall improvement."}},{"filePath":"src/PublicApi/CatalogItemEndpoints/CreateCatalogItemEndpoint.cs","title":"Replace CountAsync with AnyAsync for duplicate check","scope":"narrow","rootCause":"## Evidence\n\nAt `CreateCatalogItemEndpoint.cs:43-45`, the duplicate name check uses `CountAsync`:\n\n```csharp\nvar catalogItemNameSpecification = new CatalogItemNameSpecification(request.Name);\nvar existingCataloogItem = await itemRepository.CountAsync(catalogItemNameSpecification);\nif (existingCataloogItem > 0)\n```\n\nThe `CatalogItemNameSpecification` at `CatalogItemNameSpecification.cs:10` filters by name:\n\n```csharp\nQuery.Where(item => catalogItemName == item.Name);\n```\n\nThis generates `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM Catalog WHERE Name = @p0`. The `Name` column has a max length of 50 (`CatalogItemConfiguration.cs:19`) but no dedicated index â€” the only index is the primary key on `Id`. As items accumulate during the load test (each iteration creates a new item), the table grows and the unindexed scan becomes progressively slower.\n\n## Theory\n\n`COUNT(*)` must scan all matching rows to produce an exact count, whereas `EXISTS` (generated by `AnyAsync`) can short-circuit after finding the first match. With the load test creating hundreds of items, and no index on `Name`, each create request triggers a full table scan. Using `AnyAsync` instead of `CountAsync` allows the query to stop at the first matching row, and the Ardalis.Specification `RepositoryBase` supports `AnyAsync` natively.\n\n## Proposed Fixes\n\n1. **Replace `CountAsync` with `AnyAsync`:** Change line 44 from `CountAsync(catalogItemNameSpecification)` to `AnyAsync(catalogItemNameSpecification)`, and update the condition on line 45 to check the boolean result directly. This generates an `EXISTS` query that short-circuits.\n\n## Expected Impact\n\n- p95 latency: ~0.05-0.1ms reduction per create request\n- The create endpoint accounts for ~14.3% of traffic. The per-request improvement is modest (~0.05ms), yielding ~0.4% overall p95 improvement. The benefit grows as the table size increases during the test.","impactEstimate":{"trafficPct":14.3,"latencyReductionMs":0.05,"overallP95ImprovementPct":0.4,"confidence":"medium","reasoning":"Create endpoint is 1 of 7 requests (~14.3% traffic). Switching COUNT to EXISTS saves ~0.05ms per request as the table grows. At 1.77ms p95, overall improvement is modest at ~0.4%."}}]}
